On Mon, Oct 8, 2012 at 1:03 PM, Eric J. Bowman &lt;eric@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Paul Cohen wrote:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; My understanding of coupling in the context of data types is quite the
&gt;&gt; opposite! Also I don&#39;t see that REST deals with data types at all -
&gt;&gt; standardized or not.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt; OMG, standardized media types are a key concept of REST,

Yes indeed. But media types /= data types. The web works fine without
being recompiled every morning.

&gt;&gt; I don&#39;t think you understood what I meant. I used the term &quot;coupling&quot;
&gt;&gt; in the sense that this client requirement on the server (of
&gt;&gt; maintaining URI:s) leads to undesired consequences for the developers
&gt;&gt; and the server.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Client requests old URL.  Server responds 308 with new URL.  Client
&gt; updates bookmark, never requests obsolete URL again.  There is no
&gt; coupling here, by any definition of the term.

I am not arguing against that this is good behaviour on the part of
the server. I&#39;m saying that there should be no formal requirement for
a server to maintain (for ever) all URI:s that have been exposed to
clients.

We don&#39;t seem to have the same understanding of the terms involved or
problem, so I&#39;m leaving the discussion for now.

